  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Here <math altimg="si94.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>±</mo></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>±</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math> are the black-hole (event and inner) horizons</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">25</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Here the radial coordinate y is defined by the relation <math altimg="si95.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>d</mi><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo><mi>d</mi><mi>r</mi></math></subfield>
    <subfield code="t">tortoise</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">26</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="h">Rosa, J.G.</subfield>
    <subfield code="v">1006</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">2010</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">27</subfield>
    <subfield code="s">J.High Energy Phys.,1006,015</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">In particular, since each inequality in (15) roughly corresponds to an order-of-magnitude difference between two quantities, one concludes that the resonance condition (11) should be valid in the regime <math altimg="si102.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>m</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">H</mi></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>ω</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><msqrt><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></msqrt><mo>≲</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">28</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">One finds that <math altimg="si54.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>β</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></math> in the regime <math altimg="si97.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>α</mi><mo>≤</mo><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><msqrt><mrow><mn>2</mn><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>l</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></msqrt><mo>-</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>2</mn></math>, see Eq. (21) below</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">29</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">This physical parameter provides a quantitative measure for the deviation of the resonant oscillation frequency <math altimg="si75.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">R</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> from the field mass parameter μ</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">30</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Compare this property of the non-hydrogenic spectrum (24) with the familiar hydrogenic spectrum (4) which is known to be degenerate</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">31</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">This is the largest black-hole spin for which we have exact (numerical) data [12] for the characteristic oscillation frequencies <math altimg="si98.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">R</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi>μ</mi></math> of the quasi-stationary bound-state resonances. Note that the numerical results of [9] indicate that, for <math altimg="si99.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>α</mi><mo>≲</mo><mn>0.6</mn></math> and <math altimg="si100.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>a</mi><mo stretchy="false">→</mo><msup><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>, the values of the fundamental resonant frequencies <math altimg="si101.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">R</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi>μ</mi></math> depend very weakly on the black-hole rotation parameter a (see, in particular, Fig. 5 of [9] )</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">32</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">As discussed above, our resonance equation (11) is restricted to the regime <math altimg="si102.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>m</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">H</mi></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>ω</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><msqrt><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></msqrt><mo>≲</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math> [28]. Substituting our solution (24) into the left-hand-side of (16), one finds that, for the fundamental <math altimg="si68.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> mode, the requirement <math altimg="si102.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>m</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">H</mi></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>ω</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><msqrt><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mrow><mi>ω</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></msqrt><mo>≲</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math> is respected in the regime <math altimg="si103.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>α</mi><mo>≲</mo><mn>0.58</mn></math>. Note that this mass regime is consistent with our previous requirement <math altimg="si54.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>β</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></math> [29], which implies the weaker restriction <math altimg="si104.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>α</mi><mo>≲</mo><mn>0.67</mn></math> for the fundamental <math altimg="si68.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> mode</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">33</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Note that Eqs. (21) and (23) yield <math altimg="si105.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msubsup><mrow><mi>β</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>≃</mo><mn>1.057</mn></math> and <math altimg="si106.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>ϵ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>≃</mo><mn>0.097</mn></math> for the fundamental <math altimg="si68.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> mode with <math altimg="si70.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0.42</mn></math>. One therefore finds the characteristic small ratio <math altimg="si107.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi>β</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>≃</mo><mn>0.009</mn><mo>≪</mo><mn>1</mn></math>. This strong inequality justifies our previous assumption <math altimg="si108.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi>β</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>≪</mo><mn>1</mn></math> [see Eq. (20)]. Moreover, since <math altimg="si74.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>ϵ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> is a decreasing function of the resonance parameter n [see Eq. (23)], one finds that the approximation <math altimg="si108.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi>β</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>≪</mo><mn>1</mn></math> becomes even better for the excited ( <math altimg="si109.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>n</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>1</mn></math> ) resonant modes</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">34</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">The only exception is the excited <math altimg="si110.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math> mode, for which the agreement between the numerically computed deviation-parameter <math altimg="si111.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>ϵ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">num</mi></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> and the analytical formulas (4) and (24) is quite poor</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">35</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Note that this parameter is an integer</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">36</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">Note that, for generic values of the mass parameter α, the generalized (finite-mass) spheroidal harmonic index <math altimg="si66.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>ℓ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>α</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> that appears in the resonance spectrum (24) is not an integer</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">37</subfield>
  </datafield>
